Returning to our discussion of FSMs from Monday:¶

Once we decide on a set of states for an FSM design, and we draw a state transition diagram, what is our next step?

State Transition Table¶

A state transition table allows us to codify the logic represented in a state transition diagram

Transition Start Condition End
A state 1 (insert logic) state 1
B state 1 (insert logic) state 2
C state 2 (insert logic) state 2
Transition Start Condition End
A state 1 (insert logic) state 1
B state 1 (insert logic) state 2
C state 2 (insert logic) state 2

The key thing to note about a transition is that it includes context as well as a logical stimulus. When "reading" the table, we read "for transition A to be true, the machine must be in state 1 and the condition must be true."

Example: Romi "Box"¶

For the class exercise you completed, we could say that the Romi is either "going straight" or "turning". Drawing these two states is the first step in our design.

Example: Romi "Box"¶

Next, we can determine the structure of our FSM by deciding how the system can move between states.

Finally, we can decide what stimuli will cause these transitions and fill out our table.

Transition Start Condition End
A straight change in distance < L straight
B straight change in distance >= L turn
C turn change in angle < 90 turn
D turn change in angle >= 90 straight

Let's re-configure this table to allow us to "test" the FSM using the keyboard!¶

Transition Start Condition End
A straight not press 'k' straight
B straight press 'k' turn
C turn not press 'k' turn
D turn press 'k' straight

How do we Implement an FSM?¶

Using prof. Brown's "four block structure" makes it very straightforward to turn your state transition diagram into a functioning FSM implementation. The structure is given below.

Block 1: Process User Inputs & Sensors¶

Block 1 is also where the program needs to take any "raw" inputs from the user and process/translate them for use in the state transition logic. For example, if your design requires you to hold a button for 2 seconds, you may need to write some logic that uses a "timer" (which we will cover later) to check how long a certain momentary button has been held.

Block 1 Example - Unique Press¶

A common task that needs to go into this portion of your program is that of detecting a unique press on a momentary switch or button. Look at the time history of a momentary button press below:

Implementing the "unique button press" logic means capturing the context that the button is true now, but was false last time I looked.

BTN_PRESS = Button_State && !OLD_Button_State;

In Python code, this might look like:

BTN_PRESS = Button_State and not(OLD_Button_State)

Of course, this is just one example of what "Block 1" of your program should contain. In summary, it needs to update the value of anything that will be used to evaluate the state transition logic in the next block.

Class Example: Block 1 to detect a "unique press"¶

We will use the keyboard module in Webots's "controller" python library for this exercise. Our goal is to have Webots detect a unique press on a specific key (in this case, the 'k' key). Documentation of the keyboard functionality in Webots is available here.

Step 1: Clone a new copy of the ES302_Webots repository into your student work folder (or anywhere on your computer)¶

  • Create a new ES302 Webots workspace using the following commands:
git clone https://github.com/Alexanderallenbrown/ES302_Webots.git my_folder_name
cd my_folder_name
git submodule update --init
git submodule update

or, just make a copy of your last in-class exercise folder!

Step 2: open the romi_demo world, and modify the romi_demo controller.¶

After the romi is defined in the file, pull out the "keyboard" sensor instance and enable it.

romi = Romi(sim=True)
keyboard = romi.simromi.getKeyboard()
print(keyboard)
keyboard.enable(int(romi.simromi.getBasicTimeStep()))

Then, in the While loop, add functionality to print the key currently pressed.

while romi.simromi.step(timestep) != -1:
    print(keyboard.getKey())

Run the simulation, click on the 3D window, and then press the "k" key to see the key code corresponding with this key (75).

Step 3: Implement a "unique press" system to detect presses on key 'k'¶

romi = Romi(sim=True)
keyboard = romi.simromi.getKeyboard()
print(keyboard)
keyboard.enable(int(romi.simromi.getBasicTimeStep()))
oldKey
...
while romi.simromi.step(timestep) != -1:
    keyNow = keyboard.getKey()
    uniqueK = (keyNow==75) and (oldKey!=75)
    oldKey = keyNow

    print(uniqueK)

verify that uniqueK goes 'true' for one loop only when 'k' is held down.

Block 2: Evaluate State Transition Logic¶

To write the code for block 2, simply write a single line of code representing to the boolean expression for each transition in your state transition table without including the ending state.

How would we implement the transitions from our 'test' FSM in code?¶

B straight press 'k' turn
C turn not press 'k' turn
D turn press 'k' straight

How would we implement the transitions from our 'test' FSM in code?¶

Transition Start Condition End
A straight not press 'k' straight
B straight press 'k' turn
C turn not press 'k' turn
D turn press 'k' straight

The Block 2 lines can be written by reading directly across the first three columns of the table!

A=straight and not uniqueK
B=straight and uniqueK
C=turn and not uniqueK
D=turn and uniqueK

Block 3: Set the FSM's State.¶

Look at each state in your diagram. The ways in which any state can be true is that any of the transitions that point to it are true!! This means, for our example, that block 3 looks like this:

straight = A or D
turn = B or C

Block 4: Activate Outputs For Current State and Update Variables¶

Once you know what state your machine is in, you can use "if" statements to perform actions based on the state the machine is in!!

if(straight):
    romiGoForward()
elif(turn):
    romiTurnLeft()
else:
    print("OOPS! not in a state!)
